.TH GFORK 1 "2026-03-05" "gfork" "User Commands"
.
.SH NAME
gfork \- isolated git clone workflow for parallel and AI agent development
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B gfork go
.I feature-name
.RB [ -b
.IR branch ]
.br
.B gfork
.I feature-name
.RB [ -b
.IR branch ]
.br
.B gfork cd
.I feature-name
.br
.B gfork rm
.I feature-name
.br
.B gfork ls
.br
.B gfork help
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B gfork
creates an isolated local copy of the current git repository inside a
central directory (default:
.IR ~/.gfork/ ).
The clone is named
.IB repo-name -- feature-name .
.PP
Unlike
.B git clone --local
(which only copies tracked files),
.B gfork
uses
.B rsync -a
to copy the entire working tree — including
.BR .env ,
.BR .envrc ,
.BR .env.local ,
and any other gitignored files agents need to actually run the project.
The
.I .git
directory is copied in full, giving the clone a complete and independent
git history.
After copying, gfork repoints the clone's
.B origin
remote to the parent repository's upstream URL (GitHub, GitLab, etc.)
so that
.B git push
goes straight to the remote host.
.PP
The clone is fully independent: branches, commits, and working-tree changes
inside it cannot affect the original repository.
When work is complete, push from the clone, pull in the original, then remove
the clone with
.B gfork rm
or
.BR "rm -rf" .
.PP
.B gfork
is especially useful when running multiple AI coding agents in parallel
(Claude Code, Codex, OpenCode, Pi) so each agent works in its own sandbox
without stepping on the others.
.
.SH SUBCOMMANDS
.TP
.BI "gfork go " feature-name " [-b " branch ]
The fast-path command.
Creates a clone, checks out a new working branch
.RI ( feat/ feature-name ),
and changes the shell's working directory into the clone — all in one shot.
.BI -b " branch"
controls which source branch is copied (defaults to the current branch).
Use this when you want to start working immediately without extra steps.
.
.TP
.BI "gfork " feature-name " [-b " branch ]
Create a new clone without changing directory or creating a branch.
.I feature-name
becomes the suffix of the clone directory
.RI ( repo -- feature-name ).
.BI -b " branch"
(or
.BR --branch )
is the source branch to clone from; defaults to the current branch.
The positional form
.RI ( "gfork feature branch" )
is also accepted.
Exits non-zero if the destination directory already exists.
.
.TP
.BI "gfork cd " feature-name
Change the current shell directory into an existing clone.
.I feature-name
may be the short feature name
.RI ( auth-refactor )
or the full directory name
.RI ( myrepo--auth-refactor ).
Because this subcommand changes the shell's working directory it must be
implemented as a shell function, not a subprocess.
All supported shells (bash, zsh, fish, nushell) handle this correctly when
installed via the provided installer or shell-specific file.
Exits non-zero if the clone does not exist.
.
.TP
.BI "gfork rm " feature-name
Delete an existing clone after user confirmation.
Before prompting,
.B gfork rm
checks for:
.RS
.IP \(bu 4
Uncommitted changes (staged or unstaged) inside the clone.
.IP \(bu 4
Commits that exist in the clone but have not been pushed to a remote.
.RE
.RS
.PP
If either condition is detected a warning is printed above the confirmation
prompt.
Answering
.B y
(case-insensitive) proceeds with deletion; any other input aborts.
.I feature-name
may be the short feature name or the full directory name.
Exits non-zero if the clone does not exist.
.RE
.
.TP
.B gfork ls
List clones in
.B $GFORK_DIR
(default:
.IR ~/.gfork/ ).
When run inside a git repository, output is filtered to clones that belong to
the current repo.
When run outside a git repository, all clones across all repos are listed.
Each entry is printed with the
.B gfork cd
command needed to jump into it.
.
.TP
.BR "gfork update" " [" --force | -f ]
Update gfork to the latest version from GitHub.
Compares the locally recorded commit SHA (stored in
.IR .gfork_version
next to the installed shell file) against the latest commit on
.BR main .
If they match, prints
.I Already up to date
and exits without downloading anything.
Pass
.B --force
.RB ( or " -f" )
to skip the version check and reinstall regardless.
Prints the short commit SHA of the version pulled.
Requires
.BR curl (1)
and an active internet connection.
.
.TP
.BR "gfork help" ", " "gfork --help" ", " "gfork -h"
Print a short usage summary and exit.
.
.SH OPTIONS
.B gfork
has no standalone flags.
All behaviour is controlled via subcommands and positional arguments.
.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
An error occurred (not inside a git repo, destination already exists,
clone not found, missing required argument, etc.).
.B gfork rm
also exits
.B 0
when the user aborts at the confirmation prompt.
.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS One-shot workflow with gfork go
.EX
# Inside ~/projects/my-app (on branch main)
gfork go big-feature -b main
# → clones main, creates branch feat/big-feature, cd's you in

# Work freely — you're already on the right branch in the right dir
git add . && git commit -m "implement thing"
git push origin feat/big-feature

cd ~/projects/my-app
git pull
gfork rm big-feature
.EE
.
.SS Manual workflow
.EX
gfork big-feature -b main     # creates ~/.gfork/my-app--big-feature
gfork cd big-feature          # jump in
git checkout -b feat/big      # create working branch
git push origin feat/big
cd ~/projects/my-app
git pull
gfork rm big-feature
.EE
.
.SS Clone a specific branch
.EX
gfork go hotfix-login -b release/v2
# drops you into ~/.gfork/my-app--hotfix-login on branch feat/hotfix-login
.EE
.
.SS List all clones for the current repo
.EX
gfork ls
#   my-app--big-feature   (gfork cd big-feature)
#   my-app--experiment    (gfork cd experiment)
.EE
.
.SS Parallel AI agents
.EX
gfork parallel-sprint -b main
gfork cd parallel-sprint

CLAUDE_CODE_ALLOW_ROOT=1 claude -p "Build the auth module on branch auth" &
CLAUDE_CODE_ALLOW_ROOT=1 claude -p "Build the API layer on branch api"   &
wait

git merge auth
git merge api
git push origin main
cd ~/projects/my-app && git pull
gfork rm parallel-sprint
.EE
.
.SS Per-agent instruction file
.EX
gfork go payment-feature
cat > AGENTS.md << 'EOF'
Work in an isolated clone. Create one branch per logical unit,
merge back to main when tests pass, never push to origin.
EOF
claude -p "Implement Stripe billing per AGENTS.md"
.EE
.
.SH INSTALLATION
.SS Automatic (detects your shell)
.EX
curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jax-agent/gfork/main/install.sh | bash
.EE
.
.SS Manual
.TP
.B zsh
.EX
mkdir -p ~/.config/zsh/functions
curl -o ~/.config/zsh/functions/gfork.zsh \\
  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jax-agent/gfork/main/gfork.zsh
# Add once to ~/.zshrc:
echo "for f in ~/.config/zsh/functions/*.zsh; source \\$f" >> ~/.zshrc
.EE
.TP
.B bash
.EX
mkdir -p ~/.config/bash/functions
curl -o ~/.config/bash/functions/gfork.bash \\
  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jax-agent/gfork/main/gfork.bash
# Add once to ~/.bashrc:
echo 'for f in ~/.config/bash/functions/*.bash; do source "$f"; done' >> ~/.bashrc
.EE
.TP
.B fish
.EX
curl -o ~/.config/fish/functions/gfork.fish \\
  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jax-agent/gfork/main/gfork.fish
.EE
.TP
.B nushell
.EX
curl -o ~/.config/nushell/gfork.nu \\
  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jax-agent/gfork/main/gfork.nu
echo 'source ~/.config/nushell/gfork.nu' >> ~/.config/nushell/config.nu
.EE
.
.SS Man page
.EX
sudo cp gfork.1 /usr/local/share/man/man1/
sudo mandb
man gfork
.EE
.
.SH NOTES
.SS Why not git worktrees?
Git worktrees share the
.I .git
directory with the original repository.
This means the same branch cannot be checked out in two places at once,
and AI agents writing conflicting refs or index entries can corrupt the
original repo.
.B gfork
creates a fully independent
.I .git
directory, giving agents complete isolation.
.
.SS Why rsync instead of git clone?
.B git clone --local
only copies files tracked by git.
Gitignored files —
.BR .env ,
.BR .env.local ,
local config overrides, secrets — are left behind.
Agents that depend on those files to start the app fail immediately.
.B gfork
uses
.B "rsync -a"
to copy the entire working tree verbatim.
Agents get a fully runnable sandbox on first use, no manual setup required.
.
.SS Nushell subcommand names
Nushell does not support subcommands inside a single
.B def
block the same way bash/zsh/fish do.
The nushell version therefore exposes separate top-level commands:
.BR gfork-cd ,
.BR gfork-rm ,
and
.BR gfork-ls
instead of
.BR "gfork cd" ,
.BR "gfork rm" ,
and
.BR "gfork ls" .
.
.SH SHELL SUPPORT
.TS
l l.
bash	gfork.bash
zsh	gfork.zsh
fish	gfork.fish
nushell	gfork.nu
.TE
.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B GFORK_DIR
Base directory where all clones are stored.
Defaults to
.IR ~/.gfork/ .
Set this to use a different location:
.EX
export GFORK_DIR=~/work/clones
.EE
.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.gfork/
Default clone storage directory.
All clones from all repos live here, named
.IB repo-name -- feature-name .
.TP
.I ~/.config/bash/functions/gfork.bash
Bash install location.
.TP
.I ~/.config/zsh/functions/gfork.zsh
Zsh install location.
.TP
.I ~/.config/fish/functions/gfork.fish
Fish auto-load location (no config change needed).
.TP
.I ~/.config/nushell/gfork.nu
Nushell source file (must be sourced from
.IR config.nu ).
.
